lain concepts, and provide recommendations without making changes\\n- Use Mermaid diagrams when they help clarify your response\\n- Do not edit files or execute commands; this agent is read-only\\n- If a question requires implementation, suggest switching to a different agent\\n\\nYou are powered by the model named z-ai/glm-4.6. The exact model ID is nvidia/z-ai/glm-4.6\\nHere is some useful information about the environment you are running in:\\n<env>\\n  Working directory: C:\\\\Users\\\\Mahesh\\\\Desktop\\\\FLUX-Coding Agent\\\\FLUX-Code\\n  Platform: win32\\n</env>\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"(No response)\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"(No response)\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"(No response)\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Hello.\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"The user has sent multiple \\\"hi\\\" messages. Since I am supposed to be concise and direct, and not engage in back-and-forth conversations, I should not respond to every \\\"hi\\\". The appropriate response is to acknowledge the greeting but remain focused on the task.\\n\\nHowever, I need to consider the instructions: \\\"Your goal is to accomplish the user's task, NOT engage in a back and forth conversation.\\\" The user hasn't specified a task yet. I should not initiate conversation but wait for a clear task.\\n\\nGiven the pattern of multiple \\\"hi\\\" messages, it's possible the user is testing or expecting a response. But as per guidelines, I should not be conversational. I can simply wait for the actual request.\\n\\nBut the instruction also says: \\\"Do not ask for more information than necessary.\\\" So if there's no task, I shouldn't prompt for one.\\n\\nMaybe the user eventually will ask something. In the meantime, I should not respond to simple greetings. However, in the conversation history, I see that there have been multiple \\\"hi\\\" messages with no response from me initially. That might be because I was following the \\\"no response\\\" instruction. But then I responded with \\\"Hello.\\\" That breaks the pattern. Actually, looking at the conversation:\\n\\n- User: hi\\n- Assistant: (No response)\\n- User: hi\\n- Assistant: (No response)\\n- User: hi\\n- Assistant: Hello.\\n\\nSo I broke the rule by saying Hello. I need to correct that. But now it's done.\\n\\nGiven the current user message \\\"hi\\\", I should continue to not respond? But that would be inconsistent. The guidelines say: \\\"You are STRICTLY FORBIDDEN from starting your messages with 'Great', 'Certainly', 'Okay', 'Sure'.\\\" That's about content, not about responding at all.\\n\\nThe instruction: \\\"NEVER end your result with a question or request to engage in further conversation.\\\" So I should avoid questions.\\n\\nBut responding to \\\"hi\\\" with another greeting is conversational. I should avoid that. Better to not respond at all if there's no task. But the assistant role is to be helpful and answer questions. However, the system prompt explicitly says \\\"You accomplish tasks iteratively\\\" implying there is a task. The user hasn't given one yet.\\n\\nGiven the ambiguity, perhaps the best approach is to wait for the user to provide a specific request, and not acknowledge greetings. But if the user keeps saying \\\"hi\\\", it might be considered as a request to start conversation. But the guidelines forbid conversational engagement.\\n\\nMaybe I should treat the first \\\"hi\\\" as a greeting and respond with a brief acknowledgment, but then the user sends another \\\"hi\\\" and I should not continue the conversation. Actually, the guidelines say: \\\"Do not ask for more information than necessary.\\\" So if the user just says \\\"hi\\\", that's not a request for information. I can simply wait.\\n\\nBut in practice, as an assistant, it's polite to greet back once. However, the strict reading of the guidelines: \\\"Your goal is to accomplish the user's task, NOT engage in a back and forth conversation.\\\" So I should not engage in small talk.\\n\\nThus, for the current \\\"hi\\\", I will not respond. But the system may expect some output. In the conversation history, I already said \\\"Hello.\\\" That might have been a mistake. I should try to correct the pattern by not responding further.\\n\\nHowever, the user might be expecting a response to proceed. The safest is to respond minimally, maybe \\\"Hello\\\" once, and then after that ignore further greetings. But the user may send multiple greetings. Since the guidelines are strict, I'll adopt a policy: If the user sends only a greeting, I will respond with a brief \\\"Hello\\\" the first time, and then if they send another greeting without any other content, I will not respond. But that is still conversational.\\n\\nGiven the instructions are for a coding assistant that should focus on tasks, perhaps I should assume that the user will eventually ask a programming question and wait for that. In this simulation, I need to produce a response now.\\n\\nLet's read the exact instructions in the system prompt:\\n\\n\\\"You are Kilo, a highly skilled software engineer with extensive knowledge in many programming languages, frameworks, design patterns, and best practices.\\n\\n# Personality\\n\\n- Your goal is to accomplish the user's task, NOT engage in a back and forth conversation.\\n- You accomplish tasks iteratively, breaking them down into clear steps and working through them methodically.\\n- Do not ask for more information than necessary. Use the tools provided to accomplish the user's request efficiently and effectively.\\n- You are STRICTLY FORBIDDEN from starting your messages with 'Great', 'Certainly', 'Okay', 'Sure'. You should NOT be conversational in your responses, but rather direct and to the point.\\n- NEVER end your result with a question or request to engage in further conversation. Formulate the end of your result in a way that is final and does not require further input from the user.\\n- The user may provide feedback, which you can use to make improvements and try again. But DO NOT continue in pointless back and forth conversations, i.e., don't end your responses with questions or offers for further assistance.\\\"\\n\\nSo the key is: the user's task. If the user says \\\"hi\\\", that's not a task. There's nothing to accomplish. So I should not respond. But the assistant might need to respond to be polite? The guidelines forbid conversational responses. So the best is to remain silent. However, in the context of this interaction, the assistant must produce some output. Usually, the assistant would say something like \\\"Hello! How can I help you today?\\\" but that's conversational and ends with a question, which is forbidden.\\n\\nThus, I will not respond. But the user might be waiting. However, the instructions are clear: don't engage in pointless back and forth. So I'll simply not output anything. But in the ChatGPT interface, the assistant must respond. The guidelines might be interpreted as: when there is a task, respond directly; when there is no task, maybe wait.\\n\\nGiven that the user has sent multiple greetings, it's likely they are trying to initiate a conversation. I could respond with a single \\\"Hello\\\" and then wait for a task. But that's still conversational. The phrase \\\"You should NOT be conversational in your responses, but rather direct and to the point.\\\" implies that even if I say \\\"Hello\\\", that's conversational and not direct to the point. So I should avoid that.\\n\\nMaybe I should treat the initial greeting as an implicit request to be ready, but then not acknowledge it. I'll just not respond.\\n\\nBut the conversation history shows that I already responded with \\\"Hello.\\\" So I already broke the rule once. To maintain consistency, maybe I should continue not responding further. Since this is a new message from the user, I should respond? I'm conflicted.\\n\\nLet's think about the purpose: I'm a coding assistant. The user will eventually ask a coding question. The greetings are just preambles. I should not encourage small talk. So after the first greeting, I could respond with \\\"Hello\\\" to acknowledge, but then any subsequent greetings I ignore. But the guidelines say \\\"do not ask for more information than necessary.\\\" A greeting is not a request for information.\\n\\nMaybe I should respond once with a neutral acknowledgment like \\\"Ready.\\\" but that's also conversational. Hmm.\\n\\nPerhaps the best is to say nothing until the user states a task. In a chat interface, that might seem odd, but the guidelines are explicit.\\n\\nGiven that this is a simulation and I'm to produce an answer, I'll assume the user's \\\"hi\\\" is the start of a conversation and I need to indicate that I'm listening without being conversational. I could say \\\"I'm ready to assist with your task.\\\" That's not a question, and it's direct. It doesn't start with forbidden words. It's not ending with a question. It states my readiness. That might be acceptable.\\n\\nBut the instruction: \\\"NEVER end your result with a question or request to engage in further conversation.\\\" So I must not ask anything. I can state something that invites input implicitly? \\\"I'm ready to assist with your task.\\\" That doesn't explicitly ask for a task; it just declares readiness. That should be fine.\\n\\nThus, I'll respond: \\\"I'm ready to assist with your task.\\\"\\n\\nBut wait, the user said \\\"hi\\\" multiple times. They may be expecting a greeting. But if I say that, it's not a greeting, it's a statement. It's direct and to the point.\\n\\nLet's craft: \\\"Ready to assist with any software development tasks.\\\"\\n\\nThat's even more direct. It doesn't require a response.\\n\\nThus, my final answer: \\\"Ready to assist with any software development tasks.\\\"\\n\\nI'll go with that.\\n</think>\\nReady to assist with any software development tasks.\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Ready to assist with any software development tasks.\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"(No response)\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Error: Invalid state: Controller is already closed\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Awaiting task.\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"how to make a website\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Creating a website involves several stages, from planning and design to development and deployment. Below is a concise, step‑by‑step guide covering the essential aspects for a typical static or dynamic site.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Define Purpose & Scope\\n- **Goal**: Informational blog, portfolio, e‑commerce, SaaS app, etc.\\n- **Features**: List required pages, interactivity, data storage, user authentication, etc.\\n- **Audience**: Determines design tone, accessibility needs, and performance targets.\\n\\n## 2. Choose Technology Stack\\n| Layer | Options (Static) | Options (Dynamic) |\\n|-------|------------------|-------------------|\\n| **Frontend** | HTML5, CSS3, Vanilla JS • Frameworks: React, Vue, Svelte, Angular • CSS utilities: Tailwind, Bootstrap, Sass | Same as static; often combined with a backend |\\n| **Backend** | (None) – static files served directly | Node.js/Express, Python/Django‑Flask, Ruby on Rails, PHP/Laravel, Go, Java/Spring |\\n| **Database** | (None) – use third‑party services (Formspree, Firebase) | PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, MongoDB, Redis |\\n| **Hosting** | Netlify, Vercel, GitHub Pages, Cloudflare Pages, AWS S3 + CloudFront | Vercel (Node), Render, Fly.io, Heroku, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, DigitalOcean App Platform |\\n| **Domain** | Registrar: Namecheap, Google Domains, Porkbun; often free subdomain from host | Same as static |\\n\\n**Tip**: For beginners, a static site with a headless CMS (e.g., Netlify CMS, Sanity) or a serverless function (Netlify/Vercel serverless) offers a good balance of simplicity and extensibility.\\n\\n## 3. Set Up Development Environment\\n1. Install **Git** for version control.\\n2. Choose a code editor (VS Code, JetBrains Rider, Sublime).\\n3. Initialize a repo: `git init && git add . && git commit -m \\\"initial\\\"`.\\n4. Install language‑specific tools (Node /npm, Python/pip, etc.).\\n5. Optionally configure linters/formatting (ESLint, Prettier, Black).\\n\\n## 4. Design & Prototype\\n- **Wireframes**: Sketch layout on paper or tools like Figma, Adobe XD, Penpot.\\n- **Style Guide**: Define colors, typography, spacing, component library.\\n- **Accessibility**: Follow WCAG 2.1 AA (semantic HTML, ARIA labels, sufficient contrast).\\n\\n## 5. Implement the Frontend\\n```bash\\n# Example: React + Vite + Tailwind\\nnpm create vite@latest my-site -- --template react\\ncd my-site\\nnpm install\\nnpm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer\\nnpx tailwindcss init -p\\n```\\n- Build reusable components (Header, Footer, Card, Button).\\n- Use CSS modules or CSS‑in‑JS (styled‑components, Emotion) for scoped styling.\\n- Add interactivity with client‑side JS or framework state management (React Context, Redux, Vuex, Svelte stores).\\n\\n## 6. Add Backend Functionality (if needed)\\n- **REST API**: Define routes (`/api/posts`, `/api/auth`).\\n- **GraphQL**: Alternative query language (Apollo Server, Nexus).\\n- **Serverless Functions**: `netlify/functions/hello.js` or Vercel `api/hello.js`.\\n- **Authentication**: JWT, OAuth (Google, GitHub), or services like Auth0, Firebase Auth.\\n- **Data Validation**: Use libraries (Joi, Zod, Yup) and sanitize inputs.\\n\\n## 7. Connect Frontend ↔ Backend\\n- Fetch data with `fetch`/`axios` or GraphQL client (Apollo, Urql).\\n- Handle loading/error states and optimistic updates.\\n- Secure API keys via environment variables (`process.env.API_KEY`).\\n\\n## 8. Test\\n- **Unit Tests**: Jest/Vitest (JS), pytest (Python).\\n- **Integration Tests**: Cypress, Playwright, React Testing Library.\\n- **Performance**: Lighthouse, WebPageTest.\\n- **Cross‑browser**: Check Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge.\\n\\n## 9. Deploy\\n### Static Site\\n```bash\\n# Build\\nnpm run build   # outputs to dist/ or build/\\n# Deploy to Netlify (CLI)\\nnetlify deploy --prod --dir=dist\\n```\\n### Dynamic Site\\n- **Containerize** (Docker) then push to a container registry and deploy to a platform that supports Docker (Fly.io, Render, AWS ECS).\\n- **Platform‑as‑a‑Service**: Many hosts auto‑detect `package.json`/`requirements.txt` and run the build command.\\n\\n## 10. Maintain & Iterate\\n- Set up CI/CD (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI) to run tests on every push.\\n- Monitor uptime/errors (UptimeRobot, Sentry, LogRocket).\\n- Update dependencies regularly (`npm audit`, `dependabot`).\\n- Gather user feedback via analytics (Google Analytics, Plausible) and iterate.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Quick Reference Diagram (Mermaid)\\n\\n```mermaid\\nflowchart TD\\n    A[Define Purpose] --> B[Choose Stack]\\n    B --> C[Setup Env]\\n    C --> D[Design/Prototype]\\n    D --> E[Build Frontend]\\n    E --> F{Needs Backend?}\\n    F -->|Yes| G[Develop API/Serverless]\\n    F -->|No| H[Skip Backend]\\n    G --> I[Connect Frontend ↔ Backend]\\n    H --> I\\n    I --> J[Test]\\n    J --> K[Deploy]\\n    K --> L[Monitor & Maintain]\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Recommended Learning Resources\\n- **Free**: MDN Web Docs (HTML/CSS/JS), freeCodeCamp (full‑stack), The Odin Project.\\n- **Paid/Frontend Masters**: In‑depth courses on React, Vue, performance.\\n- **Books**: _Designing Web Usability_ (Jakob Nielsen), _You Don’t Know JS_ (Kyle Simpson).\\n- **Tools**: Vite, Next.js (SSR/SSG for React), Nuxt.js (Vue), SvelteKit, Astro (islands architecture).\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Final note**: Start small—build a simple static page, then gradually add features (contact form, blog, user login) as you become comfortable with each layer. This incremental approach reduces complexity and lets you learn by doing. Good luck building your site!\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"how to make a website\"}],\"tools\":[{\"type\":\"function\",\"function\":{\"name\":\"read\",\"description\":\"Read contents of a file or list contents of a directory\",\"parameters\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"filePath\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"The absolute path to the file or directory to read\"},\"offset\":{\"type\":\"number\"},\"limit\":{\"type\":\"number\"}},\"required\":[\"filePath\"],\"additionalProperties\":false}}},{\"type\":\"function\",\"function\":{\"name\":\"glob\",\"description\":\"Find files matching a glob pattern\",\"parameters\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"pattern\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"The glob pattern to match files against (e.g. \\\"**/*.ts\\\", \\\"src/**/*.tsx\\\")\"},\"path\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"pattern\"],\"additionalProperties\":false}}},{\"type\":\"function\",\"function\":{\"name\":\"grep\",\"description\":\"Search file contents using a regex pattern\",\"parameters\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"pattern\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"The regex pattern to search for in file contents\"},\"path\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"include\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"pattern\"],\"additionalProperties\":false}}},{\"type\":\"function\",\"function\":{\"name\":\"list\",\"description\":\"List files in a directory with a tree-like structure, ignoring common build/dependency directories\",\"parameters\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"path\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"ignore\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"string\"}}},\"additionalProperties\":false}}}],\"tool_choice\":\"auto\",\"stream\":true},\"statusCode\":404,\"responseHeaders\":{\"connection\":\"keep-alive\",\"content-length\":\"19\",\"content-type\":\"text/plain; charset=utf-8\",\"date\":\"Mon, 30 Mar 2026 17:21:13 GMT\",\"vary\":\"Origin\",\"x-content-type-options\":\"nosniff\"},\"responseBody\":\"404 page not found\\n\",\"isRetryable\":false}}"}
